02/08: Installation of the EBB-4 platform and tie-in to the oil and gas export pipeline has been completed, and pressure has been successfully tested and certified for production start-up. However, the EBB-4 well will not begin production until completion of the three-well drilling programme and installation of a gas recycling system. Development partner PA Resources reports that a considerable volume of water was lost into the EBB-4 well during the drilling of the horizontal well, and this will need to be removed from the near-wellbore area by gas lifting using recompressed gas.

02/08: Continued bad weather further delayed project completion during January, although installation and tie-in of the EBB-5 platform is progressing. The jacket has been installed and the topside is currently being mated and welded to the jacket. Upon completion, the gas injection line and risers will be installed and commissioned, and the EBB-5 well will be tied into the onshore gas compression system.

02/14: Riser platform
This is the centre for export of processed oil and gas, as well as the centre for incoming volumes from future tie-backs from satellite fields.  The platform is designed with between 40 to 50 risers and J-tubes. Water injection and oil export pumps are also localised here. The platform has a converter module (DC/AC) for power from shore. In the first phase, the platform consists of three modules. Large sections of the weather decks on these modules have been designed so as to enable future installation of EOR (enhanced oil recovery) modules and/or handle increased production from future development phases. The dry weight of the platform deck is approximately 19,000 tonnes in the first phase and is ca. 125 metres long and 30 metres wide.

02/14: Process platform. Gas, oil and injection water are transported by pipeline to riser platform. Designed for capacity of 315,000 boe but might process up to 380,000 boe. Platform deck has 3 modules with 2 separation trains for oil and gas separation, cleaning of produced water, gas treatment and utility systems. Supported by an 8-leg steel jacket. Platform deck is 100 metres long and 23 metres wide. Weight estimated at 23,000 tonnes.

02/14: Drilling platform
The field centre is planned developed with an integrated drilling facility. This concept was selected on the basis of seabed conditions and the number of wells from the field centre. The platform deck consists of 48 slots, well intervention deck and manifolds. Supported by an eight-leg steel jacket. Predrilling is performed by a semi-submersible drilling rig through a predrilling template. The estimated weight is 15,000 tonnes dry weight. Size: 40 metres x 83 metres.
Total well quantity for Phase 1 of Johan Sverdrup is 40 to 50. But details of well location is not yet specified.

02/14: The platform deck consists of the living quarter itself, with 450 cabins, control room and utility/control system. The helideck and lifeboats are also localised here. The size is 85 x 28 metres, and it is supported by a four-leg steel jacket. The weight is approximately 16,500 tons.
Oil rsv figure is condensate. Field to come onstream in autumn of 2004. Drilling of 11 planned production wells to begin in Aug. 2003. Jacket and deck installed.

In January 2002, project development for Clearwater Port was set into motion centering on an existing offshore platform known as "Platform Grace" located 12.6 miles off the coast of Oxnard, California. By converting this existing out-of-use oil and gas structure into a receiving terminal for the re-gasification of LNG, the environmental impact will be benign, and the project will have a faster construction schedule, setting Clearwater Port to be first to market.

The existing platform will be refurbished and reconfigured for LNG re-gasification, with two floating mooring docks added that are capable of accommodating large LNG ships. Construction is set for 2008, with commercial operation by 2009. The platform will be connected through a 28-mile pipeline to the Southern California Gas Company (SoCalGas) pipeline network and storage infrastructure.
